punishment of my own?
Yet stil the regret gnaws away at me. If I’d run when I had the chance, if I’d
left and somehow escaped arrest, Maya would not have confessed. Nothing
would have been gained by teling the truth, it would have only hurt the
children. She would have never confessed if I hadn’t been caught . . .
My gaze travels slowly up the wal to the smal window in the corner, just
below the ceiling. And suddenly the answer is right there in front of me. If I
